An Analysis of Congestion in Metro Manila

Google colab link


Source: Wikimedia | patrickroque001

Abstract¶

Metro Manila, the capital city of the Philippines, having a high population density of 20,780 per square km, and saturated with establishments and opportunities, has its drawbacks manifested in the daily lives of its residents, such as worsening road traffic, housing shortage, urban poverty, and etc. Exploratory data analysis will be performed on datasets containing data on population, establishments, employment, minimum wage, and urbanization rate per region to find correlationships between the features. The results will be utilized in creating a regression model that will predict the population. Research findings indicate that the congestion in Metro Manila is the result of saturated businesses and job opportunities, as well as higher minimum wage compared with the rest of the country.

1. Introduction¶

1.1 Motivation¶

Manila, the capital city of the Philippines, has once been considered the land of many opportunities. The rapid urbanization and saturation of establishments attracted people around the country to migrate in hopes of greener pastures since the 1970s. This culture of migration still continues today with numerous drawbacks such as congested roads, lack of proper housing, urban poverty, and etc., all affecting the quality of life.

According to [TomTom's 2019 Traffic Index](https://www.tomtom.com/en_gb/traffic-index/ranking/), Metro Manila ranked 2nd in the worst road traffic in the world, placing next to Bangalore, India, both with a congestion index score of 71%. In 2019, the daily traffic for Metro Manila is composed of approximately 3.1 millon vehicles, where commuters lost 257 hours average. This is not the first time that Metro Manila ranked worst in terms of traffic in different studies.



Source: Wikimedia | Judgefloro

Proper shelter remains a problem for the Philippines, having the third-largest slum population in the region according to East Asia Pacific (EAP) report, titled "Expanding Opportunities for the Urban Poor". Housing and Urban Development Coordinating Council (HUDCC) estimated that 40 percent of informal settlers in the country are in Metro Manila, equivalent to approximately 3 million residents, or 1 of every 4 residents relies in informal housing. This reflects the shortage of affordable housing for the middle and lower class in growing cities. Those deprived of proper housing are left with increased vulnerability against natural disasters, access to infrastructures, physical safety, and tenure insecurity.

The goal of this study is find explore the relevance of the large number of establishments and opportunities in Metro Manila’s population by analyzing datasets from government agencies. Additional questions are expected to come as the research progress.

1.2 Research questions¶

  1. How severe is the population congestion in Metro Manila?
  2. What factor/s contribute to the congestion?
  3. Can the capital be deconcentrated and to what degree?

1.3 Research goals¶

  • Gather relevant datasets
  • Prepare datasets for analysis
  • Visualize and interpret results
  • Find factors contributing to congestion in Metro Manila by analzying data
  • Propose solutions based on the findings

1.4 Methods¶

Exploratory data analysis (EDA) approach will be used in this project to gather insights from datasets which includes the following steps:

  • Checking size of columns, presence of null values, and corresponding data types
  • Plotting graphs to better visualize data
  • Checking and handling for outliers
  • Using correlation heatmap to gauge relationship of features

Once done with the analysis, different regression algorithms will be used to create models that will predict the numerical population value. These models will be assessed based on several performance metrics to choose which will best perform in a simulation.

Before extracting data, a list of desired regions from the first column of the MSME dataframe will be created and to be used as a filter. Two new dataframes will be declared after, ph_establishments_by_region and ph_employment_by_region, containing the list of regions as the first column

In [ ]:
#create list of desired regions to be used as filter.
regions = ['National Capital Region (NCR)', 'Cordillera Administrative Region (CAR)', 
           'Ilocos Region', 'Cagayan Valley', 'Central Luzon', 'CALABARZON', 'MIMAROPA', 'Bicol Region', 
           'Western Visayas', 'Central Visayas', 'Eastern Visayas', 'Zamboanga Peninsula', 'Northern Mindanao', 
           'Davao Region', 'SOCCSKSARGEN', 'Caraga', 'Autonomous Region in Muslim Mindanao (ARMM)']

#declare dataframes containing regions only.
ph_establishments_by_region = pd.DataFrame(regions, columns=['Region'])
ph_employment_by_region = pd.DataFrame(regions, columns=['Region'])

For the ph_establishments_by_region dataframe, the column of total number of establishments from the MSME dataframe will be appended, year-by-year. To avoid repetitive coding, a while loop will be used to reiterate over 9 excel sheets. Checking for null values will be done afterwards.

Same process goes for the ph_establishments_by_region dataframe.

In [ ]:
#using while loop to iterate over 9 sheets
year = 2010
yearend = 2019
while(year != yearend+1):
    #import database
    sheet_name = str(year)+'LE'
    cols = 'A,C,H'
    if(year>2011):
        cols = 'A,D,I'

    df = pd.read_excel(msme_xl_url, sheet_name=sheet_name, usecols=cols)

    region_df = df.loc[df.iloc[:, 0].isin(regions)]
    region_df.columns = ['Region', 'Establishments', 'Employment']
    region_df.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)

    ph_establishments_by_region[year] = region_df.Establishments.values
    ph_employment_by_region[year] = region_df.Employment.values

    year+=1

#function to convert columns to numeric type
def cols_to_int(df):
  cols = [i for i in df.columns if i not in ["Region"]]
  for col in cols:
      df[col]=pd.to_numeric(df[col])

#function to create summarized dataframe of year
def summarized_df(year):
  df = ph_establishments_by_region[['Region', year]].copy()
  df.rename(columns={year:'Establishments'}, inplace=True)
  df['Employment'] = ph_employment_by_region[year].copy()
  df['Population'] = population_df[year].copy()
  df['PopDensity'] = density_df[year].copy()
  df['MinWage'] = min_wage_df[year].copy()
  df['UrbanizationLvl'] = urbanization_df[year].copy()
  return df

#legends

plt.title("Population and Density by Region (2015) \n")
plt.show()

CALABARZON is the most populous region followed by Metro Manila. However, the former is 27.8 times larger than the latter in terms of land area(16576.26 km² vs 619.54 16576.26 km²). This means that there are an average of 20,780 people per square kilometer in the latter. The value is an extreme outlier as shown in the chart.

4. Modeling¶

4.1 Preparing datasets for training¶

The objective of the model is to predict the population in a region according to the number of establishments and the minimum wage. Several regression algorithms that are robust to outliers will be tested along with linear.

In [ ]:
#add year column
ph_2015_df['Year'] = 2015

#create df for 2010
ph_2010_df = summarized_df(2010)
ph_2010_df['Year'] = 2010

#create new dataframe with apppended values
merged_ph_df = ph_2015_df.append(ph_2010_df).copy()
merged_ph_df.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)

#store test results and accuracy scores of each regression algorithm
score_df = pd.DataFrame(columns = ['Algorithm', 'Mean Abs Error', 'Mean ^2 Error', 'R^2 Score'])
In [ ]:
#function to store scores and test results
def store_score(algo, score_df, y_prediction):
  score_df = score_df.append({
    'Algorithm': algo,
    'Mean Abs Error' : round(sm.mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_prediction), 2), 
    'Mean ^2 Error' : round(sm.mean_squared_error(y_test, y_prediction), 2), 
    'R^2 Score': round(sm.r2_score(y_test, y_prediction), 2)},
    ignore_index=True)
  results[algo] = y_prediction
  return score_df

#function to predict and print results
def predict_ncr(factor):
  test_set = {'Establishments': [(191955*factor)],
            'Employment': [(2911554*factor)],
            'MinWage': [481],
            'UrbanizationLvl': [100]}
  test_df = pd.DataFrame(data=test_set)
  y_prediction = huber.predict(test_df)
  print('Metro Manila after moving ', (100-(factor*100)), '%')
  print('of establishments and jobs to other regions')
  print('-------------------------------------------')
  print('Population: ', y_prediction)
  print('Density   : ', (y_prediction/619.54), ' persons per square kilometers')
  print('')

6. Conclusion¶

6.1 Severity of congestion¶

  • Metro Manila is the Philippine's capital city with land area of 619.54km²
  • Population is 12.79 million
  • There are 20,780 persons per square kilometer on average

6.2 Contributing factors¶

  • High concentration of establishments
  • Saturation of establishments translates to more employment opportunities
  • Rapid growth of establishments contributed to rate of urbanization resulting to relatively higher minimum wage

6.3 Deconcentration¶

Metro Manila Population
    After Moving Percentage of
    Establishments and Employment
    to Other Regions (2015)
% Establishments Employment Population Density
100% 191,955 2,911,554 12,877,253 20,785
75% 143,966 2,183,665 10,043,710 16,212
50% 95,977 1,455,777 7,210,168 11,638
25% 47,989 727,888 4,376,626 7,064

Based on the prediction of the model, Metro Manila will remain dense for its size even after moving as much as 75% of establishments and jobs to other regions. However, the impact would greatly improve the worsening living condition in the mega city in terms of road traffic, cost of housing, urban poverty, slums, labor exploitation, and etc.

For other regions receiving the establishments, the movement would not only generate jobs but also increase its urbanization level, then the minimum wage will soon follow which should attract former city migrants to return to their native origin.
